Project Write-Up:

This project designs and builds a relational database to store and analyze multi-omics
data from a triple-negative breast cancer (TNBC) dataset (DLDCCC, Cancer Discovery 2022).
The goal was to bring together clinical data, gene expression, protein levels, and 
mutation data into a system that makes it easier to search the data and use it for biological 
analysis.

The dataset was obtained from cBioPortal and includes:
- clinical data (patient and sample-level metadata)
- gene expression data (RNA-seq)
- protein quantification data
- mutation data

A total of 59 patients and 79 samples were included in the final dataset.

The final schema consists of the following core tables:
- Patient --> stores patient-level information
- Sample --> stores information about each individual sample
- Gene --> reference table for gene identifiers
- Mutation --> stores mutation events per sample
- mRNA_expression --> gene expression values per sample
- Protein_quant --> protein abundance per sample

One patient can have many samples, one sample can have many mutations, and one gene can
have many mutations. There are also many-to-many relationships where a sample can be 
associated with many genes and a gene can be associated with many samples, which are 
represented through the mRNA_expression and Protein_quant tables. This ensures that there
is less redundancy in the data and that the relationships are defined properly. It also
allows for querying to be efficient and interpretable. 

Normalization of the data was done, which includes removing any columns that were calculated
from other data instead of being original measurements, splitting values into their own 
tables so there aren't multiple in one place, storing gene information in a single 
reference table to avoid duplication, and using combined keys to properly represent relationships
between samples and genes. The final structure of the database satisfies Third Normal Form
(3NF). 

The workflow for building and populating the database involves several stages, the order of
each script outlined in script_execution_order.md. The process begins 
with cleaning the data, where raw data files were processed using a Python script to 
remove unnecessary columns, standardize missing values, eliminate duplicates, and making sure
all IDs refer to the same thing everywhere in the database. An SQL script was written to 
create the database tables, and cleaned data was converted into SQL insert statements using 
a Python script to generate a file for populating the database. Initially, the entire database
was populated using a single SQL file. However, due to issues with performance and debugging, 
the workflow was modified to split SQL files by table, load the data sequentially, and 
fix any errors at each stage. During this process, additional Python scripts were created to 
correct issues in the SQL loading files as they arose. After successfully loading everything, 
DQL queries were used to perform tasks such as verifying row counts, confirming relationships
between tables, and ensuring the data is accurate, consistent, and reliable. 

Several columns from the raw dataset were excluded to improve the quality and structure of
the database. Specifics are outlined in decisions_and_limitations.md. Columns such as immune
modulator scores and xCell scores were removed because they are derived from other data, 
redundant, and dependent on computational methods. Storing these values could introduce
inconsistencies if recalculated using different parameters. From the raw mutation data, constant
values and annotation-level information were removed because they do not describe the mutation
itself and violate normalization, which also adds unnecessary complexity. CNA data was excluded
all together since it does not provide any meaningful value for the scope of the project. Finally,
gene panel metadata was also removed since they only describe sequencing methodology (WXS), which 
does not vary across samples and does not reflect any differences biologically. 

The limitations of this project/database design are outlined in decisions_and_limitations.md. To
reiterate, the database has a complex data loading process due to unforseen errors, such as 
remaining duplicate entries even after cleaning, missing foreign keys, and formatting issues. These
required the creation of multiple intermediate scripts to fix and regenerate SQL files. Although this
ultimately ensures accuracy in the database, it reduces the reproducibility of it compared to a more
streamlined pipeline. Additionally, this project does not include the Neo4j component due to time
constraints. This component was intended to use SQL to identify differentially expressed genes, import
those into Neo4j, analyze relationships between them, and explore gene-gene interactions. 

Overall, this project shows how complex biological data can be organized into a structured relational 
database. By carefully choosing what data to include and designing a clear layout, the database makes it 
easier to analyze gene expression, protein levels, and mutation patterns in TNBC. Although there are some
limitations, this project provides a strong starting point for incorporating Neo4j in the future and any
other future work involving exploring relationships in the data. 
